<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Except there's not two flavors, Jedi and everyone else. There's a wide variety of things people can do. Why doesn't everyone in EQ make a druid, which, it has been argued, are pretty much the premier low level class? Because there's at least some balance in the game, and alternatives are viable.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Exactly! That's why there's wookie grooming and basket weaving type skills in the game. So people can do whatever they want. I'm a Grandmaster Fisherman in EQ, and fishing in EQ would probably be similiar to &quot;basket weaving&quot; in SW:G.<br>
<br>
The point is, there are a ton of different skills you can try (700+ skills so far), so it's not like you're being forced to play a single &quot;class&quot;.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  If there were starships, I suspect you'd have plenty of fighter pilots and smugglers and all the rest.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Piloting skills will probably be related to Vehicle skills, which they will have in the release, so becoming a Pilot in the expansion shouldn't take too much additional work.<br>
<br>
There will still be smugglers. That's what the Hutt faction is all about. I've seen alot of interest in the Smuggling skills. People are asking about if they'll be able to smuggle stuff without a ship, and so far the answer is yes.<br>
They just recently announced that they're going to have spice in the game, so that'll probably be a hot smuggling item.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  And if they were that worried about everyone being Jedi, why aren't they trying to restrict bounty hunters? Look around: Almost everyone wants to be a bounty hunter since they can't be a Jedi right out of the gate. Who the hell are these guys going to be hunting?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They are &quot;restricting&quot; the bounty hunting disc by making it an advanced profession similar to the Jedi skills.<br>
As for who they'll be hunting, it depends. Starting out, it'll mostly be NPCs via the mission system. Later on they'll be able to go after players, but they won't ever get to choose who they go after.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  And to complete the comparison you raised, do you really think you'll see many players in SWG who aren't human, Zabrak (Darth Maul's race, /groan) or Wookiee? I suspect that, when I play that first free month, I'll be the only Twi'lek I see most nights.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Damn you Whiz! I was gonna be a Twi`Lek! Hrm, ok, I call blue twi'lek with lektu style TK421. You better not clone my avatar or I'll stomp you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  And they're also ignoring the valuable shorty fanbase. Where are our Jawas, damn you? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You ever seen a jawa anywhere but on Tatooine? I haven't. Bothans are considered the shorties in SW:G. I'd guess they're about 1.5m tall, which is about the size of a Dark Elf/Wood Elf in EQ.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Didn't they say SW:G is not class based but rather Skill Based? So basically any Non-Jedi concept you can come up with, I can make a Jedi with the same skills.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Um, no you can't. Skills cost points, and deviating from your main discipline skills to say, learn how to cook, will cost even more points.<br>
So, yeah, you could be a Jedi that can cook, but you will probably not be able to be a Jedi Master that can cook. You'll have to trade in cooking to get more Jedi skills.<br>
<br>
Also, there aren't classes in SW:G, but there are Professions, which are sort of like classes, but you're not confined to one. You can pick up any skills you want, at the cost of more skill points.<br>
That's supposed to fix the UO scenario of everyone being a mage/fighter. If they stick two professions that would be very powerful combined on the opposite sides of the skill web, you'd never get to 50% skill in both.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Because after Jedi, Bounty Hunters are a very popular character concept. I'm not arguing either way, I'm just saying that Jedi and Bounty Hunters should be somewhat rare, but I imagine will be both extremely popular.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It should work out like this, from everything I've seen from the Devs.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  You are correct, those will be popular. I would consider Twi'lek myself if I go with a criminal/shady background (and depending on how the graphics look).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
